On Women's Equality Day, President Donald Trump commemorates the ratification of the 19th Amendment to the Constitution, which granted women the right to vote. He highlights the accomplishments of women in various fields and acknowledges their leadership in families, communities, and the nation. The President emphasizes his administration's support for the advancement of women, citing economic policies that have created more opportunities for women and reduced the unemployment rate for women to a 65-year low. He also mentions efforts to provide financial relief for working parents and address challenges faced by mothers in the workplace, such as lack of paid leave and affordable childcare. Furthermore, the President expresses the importance of enhancing access to education and training in STEM fields for women. He proclaims August 26, 2018, as Women's Equality Day and encourages the celebration of women's achievements through appropriate programs and activities.